SIMPLE: snap
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Snap
<hw>Snap</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Snapped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Snapping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[LG. or D. <ets>snappen</ets> to
snap up, to snatch; akin to G. <ets>schnappen</ets>, MHG.
<ets>snaben</ets>, Dan. <ets>snappe</ets>, and to D. <ets>snavel</ets>
beak, bill. Cf. <er>Neb</er>, <er>Snaffle</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To break at once; to break short, as substances that
are brittle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Breaks the doors open, <qex>snaps</qex> the locks.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strike, to hit, or to shut, with a sharp
sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To bite or seize suddenly, especially with the
teeth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He, by playing too often at the mouth of death, has been
<qex>snapped</qex> by it at last.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To break upon suddenly with sharp, angry words; to
treat snappishly; -- usually with <xex>up</xex>.</def>
<rj><au>Granville.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To crack; to cause to make a sharp, cracking noise;
<as>as, to <ex>snap</ex> a whip</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>MacMorian <qex>snapped</qex> his fingers repeatedly.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To project with a snap.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>To catch out sharply (a batsman
who has just snicked a bowled ball).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To snap back</b></col> <fld>(Football)</fld>, <cd>to roll
the ball back with the foot; -- done only by the center rush, who thus
delivers the ball to the quarter back on his own side when both sides
are ranged in line.</cd><-- now passed back with the hands, but still
called "snap" --> -- <col><b>To snap off</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To
break suddenly</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To bite off
suddenly.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Snap
<hw>Snap</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To break short, or at
once; to part asunder suddenly; <as>as, a mast <ex>snaps</ex>; a needle
<ex>snaps</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But this weapon will <qex>snap</qex> short, unfaithful to the hand
that employs it.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give forth, or produce, a sharp, cracking noise;
to crack; <as>as, blazing firewood <ex>snaps</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make an effort to bite; to aim to seize with the
teeth; to catch eagerly (at anything); -- often with <xex>at</xex>;
<as>as, a dog <ex>snaps</ex>at a passenger; a fish <ex>snaps</ex> at the
bait.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To utter sharp, harsh, angry words; -- often with
<xex>at</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>snap</ex> at a child</as>.</def><-- usu.
impulsively and as a quick reaction to some perceived provocation
-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To miss fire; <as>as, the gun
<ex>snapped</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Of the eyes, to emit sudden, brief sparkles like
those of a snapping fire, as sometimes in anger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Snap
<hw>Snap</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. D. <ets>snap</ets> a snatching.
See <er>Snap</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sudden
breaking or rupture of any substance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sudden, eager bite; a sudden seizing, or effort to
seize, as with the teeth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A sudden, sharp motion or blow, as with the finger
sprung from the thumb, or the thumb from the finger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A sharp, abrupt sound, as that made by the crack of
a whip; <as>as, the <ex>snap</ex> of the trigger of a
gun</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A greedy fellow.</def>
<rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>That which is, or may be, snapped up; something
bitten off, seized, or obtained by a single quick movement; hence, a
bite, morsel, or fragment; a scrap.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He's a nimble fellow,⟦br⟧
And alike skilled in every liberal science,⟦br⟧
As having certain <qex>snaps</qex> of all.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A sudden severe interval or spell; -- applied to the
weather; <as>as, a cold <ex>snap</ex></as>.</def> <-- but not a heat
snap --> <rj><au>Lowell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A small catch or fastening held or closed by means
of a spring, or one which closes with a snapping sound, as the catch of
a bracelet, necklace, clasp of a book, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A snap beetle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>A thin, crisp cake, usually small, and flavored
with ginger; -- used chiefly in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>Briskness; vigor; energy; decision.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>Any circumstance out of which money may be made or
an advantage gained.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>Any task, labor, set of circumstances, or the like,
that yields satisfactory results or gives pleasure with little trouble
or effort, as an easy course of study, a job where work is light, a
bargain, etc.</def> <mark>[Slang, Chiefly U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>A snap shot with a firearm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>A snapshot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>16.</sn> <def>Something of no value; <as>as, not worth a
<ex>snap</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>17.</sn> <fld>(Football)</fld> <def>The action of snapping the
ball back, from the center usu. to the quarterback, which commences the
play (down), and, if the clock had stopped, restarts the timer clock; a
<cref>snap back</cref>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Snap back</b></col> <fld>(Football)</fld>, <cd>the act of
snapping back the ball.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Snap beetle</b></col>,
<it>or</it> <col><b>Snap bug</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>any beetle of the family <fam>Elateridae</fam>, which, when laid on
its back, is able to leap to a considerable height by means of a
thoracic spring; -- called also <cref>snapping beetle</cref>.</cd> --
<col><b>Snap flask</b></col> <fld>(Molding)</fld>, <cd>a flask for small
work, having its sides separable and held together by latches, so that
the flask may be removed from around the sand mold.</cd> -- <col><b>Snap
judgment</b></col>, <cd>a judgment formed on the instant without
deliberation.</cd> -- <col><b>Snap lock</b></col>, <cd>a lock shutting
with a catch or snap.</cd> -- <col><b>Snap riveting</b></col>,
<cd>riveting in which the rivets have snapheads formed by a die or
swaging tool.</cd> -- <col><b>Snap shot</b></col>, <cd>a quick offhand
shot, without deliberately taking aim.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Snap
<hw>Snap</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Done, performed, made, executed,
carried through, or the like, quickly and without deliberation; <as>as,
a <ex>snap</ex> judgment or decision; a <ex>snap</ex> political
convention</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snapdragon</ent>⟦br⟧
